# Auburn PHYS 2400 - Computational Physics Class Repository

Welcome to the Auburn PHYS 2400 repository! This repository contains code, resources, and examples for the Computational Physics class. You will find assignments, project files, and supplementary materials to aid in your learning.

## Repository Contents
- **Assignments**: Step-by-step coding exercises.
- **Examples**: Sample scripts and physics simulations.
- **Resources**: Documentation and helpful references.

## How to Use This Repository
Follow the instructions below to clone the repository, work with the files, and contribute changes.


## How to Clone This Repository

### Clone Using SSH
1. Open your terminal or command prompt.
2. Run the following command:
   ```bash
   git clone git@github.com:thevexis1/Auburn-Phys-2400.git
Clone Using HTTPS
Copy the repository HTTPS URL from GitHub:
Navigate to the repository page.
Click Code > HTTPS > Copy the URL.
Run the following command in your terminal or command prompt:
git clone https://github.com/thevexis1/Auburn-Phys-2400.git

Terminal Commands for Mac and Windows Users

For Mac Users
Open the Terminal application.
Navigate to the folder where you want to clone the repository:
cd /path/to/your/folder
Clone the repository using either SSH or HTTPS:
git clone git@github.com:thevexis1/Auburn-Phys-2400.git
OR
git clone https://github.com/thevexis1/Auburn-Phys-2400.git
Verify the repository contents:
ls

For Windows Users
Open Command Prompt or Git Bash.
Navigate to the desired folder using cd:
cd C:\path\to\your\folder
Clone the repository using either SSH or HTTPS:
git clone git@github.com:thevexis1/Auburn-Phys-2400.git
OR
git clone https://github.com/thevexis1/Auburn-Phys-2400.git
Verify the repository contents:
dir
Common Git Commands

Hereâ€™s a quick reference for commonly used Git commands:

Clone a repository:
git clone <repository-URL>
Navigate to the repository folder:
cd Auburn-Phys-2400
Check the current status of the repository:
git status
Stage changes for a commit:
git add <file-name>  # Add a specific file
git add .            # Add all changes
Commit changes with a message:
git commit -m "Your commit message"
Push changes to GitHub:
git push origin main
Pull the latest changes from GitHub:
git pull origin main
View commit history:
git log
Discard changes in a file:
git checkout -- <file>
Using GitHub Desktop

Using GitHub Desktop:
Click File > Clone Repository.
Paste the SSH or HTTPS URL into the URL field.
View Changes:
Open the Changes tab to view modified files.
Commit Changes:
Add a commit message in the text box.
Click Commit to main (or your branch).
Push Changes to GitHub:
Click Push origin to upload your commits.
Pull Changes:
Click Fetch origin to pull updates from GitHub.
Switch Branches:
Use the Branch menu to create, switch, or merge branches.
Open in Terminal:
Click Repository > Open in Terminal to perform advanced Git commands.
